properties.description: 25 homes designed with the Older Women’s Co-Housing group using PTE’s ‘fabric first’ approach which maximises the benefits of orientation, air-tightness, insulation and following the co-housing model. www.youtube.com/watch?v=9q25nbEl8rg
properties.name: New Ground (online only)

properties.description: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre, at Hornchurch Country Park, the Former RAF Hornchurch Airfield.
properties.name: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre

properties.description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
properties.name: Dorich House Museum

properties.description: Begun in 1897 and a century later is almost completed. Architects include F and E Walters (1897, the nave), Stanley Kerr Bates (1960, transepts), and Sir William Whitfield (1997, choir and apse).
properties.name: Ealing Abbey Church of St Benedict

properties.description: Grade II listed, built 1790. A central double door under a bracketed cornice hood, large sash windows with delicate glazing bars. Panelled interior. Curved entrance wall allowed carriages to turn in the narrow lane. Notable burial ground.
properties.name: Winchmore Hill Friends Meeting House & Burial Ground

properties.description: Hackney Empire is a grade II* listed building. The theatre was built as a music hall in 1901, designed by the architect Frank Matcham. It is now an exceptional variety theatre for the 21st century, serving the local community and beyond.
properties.name: Hackney Empire

properties.description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake Richamind & Christopher Whall.
properties.name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square

properties.description: 1939 Art Deco Grade II listed building refurbished in 1950, then restructured and modernised in 2014. Contains an authentically classic cinema, private salons and multimedia library.
properties.name: Institut français du Royaume-Uni

properties.description: Grade II-listed Georgian domestic building c.1760, formerly part of Bedford Estate. Interior refurbished 1924-5 to form lecture hall (restored 2014), library, bookshop and offices. Oak woodwork and green Doulton tiles line the staircase.
properties.name: The Swedenborg Society

properties.description: RIBA award-winning building.  Part listed frontage with purpose built archive and exhibition building added to the rear in 2002. The building now houses the University's Special Collections & Archives
properties.name: The Wash Houses (Formerly The Womens Library)

properties.description: Fine Victorian Gothic church with impressive windows and painted chancel. Paintings by Buckeridge and Westlake 1897. Restoration of chancel paintings was to celebrate the Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II. (2012)
properties.name: St Mary Magdalene Church

properties.description: Medieval village church, restored 1899 and again in 1952 after WWII bomb damage. 15C font and memorials from five centuries. Grade II* listed. Refurbished for 700th anniversary in 2011; bell tower and cupola restored in 2017-18.
properties.name: Bow Church – St Mary

properties.description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

On 17 & 18 Sept the 1888 beam engine will be steaming as follows:
12.30 - 1.15pm 
2.00 - 2.45pm 
3.30 - 4.15pm
properties.name: Markfield Beam Engine and House

properties.description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.
properties.name: Museum of London Docklands

properties.description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II*  landscape.
properties.name: Nunhead Cemetery

properties.description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College

properties.description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).
properties.name: St Augustine's Tower

properties.description: 6-storey building featuring a Western exterior and traditional Islamic interior, modelled on the Blue Mosque in Istanbul. Has dome and minaret tower.
properties.name: Suleymaniye Mosque

properties.description:
"ARGENTINA AT THE LONDON DESIGN FESTIVAL 2022" 
During Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to visit and explore the historic mansion host to the exhibition “Creative experience- From Argentina to the world”
properties.name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence

properties.description: The world's oldest active biological society. Founded in 1788, the Society takes its name from the Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus whose botanical, zoological and library collections have been in its keeping since 1829.
properties.name: Burlington House: Linnean Society of London

properties.description: Outdoor pool 100x33 yards. One million gallons of unheated water. Iconic outdoor cubicle doors, fountain and café added in the 1930s, with Art Deco style entrance in 2001. Sports hall pavilion added in 2016.
properties.name: Tooting Bec Lido

properties.description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.
properties.name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer

properties.description: Residence of Sir Francis Ronalds, George MacDonald and (from 1878-96) William Morris. Organised by William Morris Society. Access to The William Morris Society's premises in the Coach House and basement only, includes current exhibition.
properties.name: William Morris Society - Kelmscott House

properties.description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.
properties.name: Wimbledon Windmill

properties.description: Grade I listed pioneering brick polychromy. Designed with early Christian, Italian, Ottoman, Alhambran, Mamluk, Sevillean and Ancient Egyptian influences with fine mosaics and stained glass by Crane, Bentley. Lee and Hayward.
properties.name: Christ Church, Streatham

properties.description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
properties.name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)

properties.description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.
properties.name: St Jude on the Hill

properties.description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
properties.name: St Mary the Virgin

properties.description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.
properties.name: St Mary's Church, Battersea

properties.description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
properties.name: Bruce Castle Museum

properties.description: Opened in 1855 as centrepiece of the Metropolitan Cattle Market. The clock tower offers magnificent views over London. The clock mechanism was made by John Moore of Clerkenwell. The tower has been renovated with help from the Heritage Fund.
properties.name: Caledonian Park: Clock Tower Tours

properties.description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.
properties.name: St Lawrence Church, Morden

properties.description: The home of Conway Hall Ethical Society, an organisation renowned as a hub for free speech and progressive thought. Grade II listed building with both Arts and Crafts and Art Deco features adding to its distinctive style.
properties.name: Conway Hall

properties.description: Grade II* listed Art Deco building with well-preserved interior. Auditorium with deep coved ribs; proscenium arch flanked by fluted columns. Restoration fully funded by  donations from Zoroastrian faith community, without government grants.
properties.name: Former Grosvenor Cinema, now Zoroastrian Centre For Europe

properties.description:
Built 1863 - a large corrugated iron chapel. Inside was transformed after the last war into a battleship by local sailors for Sea Cadets. 
It has decks, portholes a Bofors Gun and alter from the set of the 1964 film Becket.
properties.name: The Tin Tabernacle / Cambridge Hall

properties.description: The church (1822 - Grade I listed) is an early and important example of Greek Revival architecture in London. Significant features include the caryatids and tower copied from the Acropolis and the atmospheric crypt.
properties.name: St Pancras Church & Crypt

properties.description: As per Grand Designs, the opening roof, the retracting loo and sliding bed-bath typify this extraordinary response to constraints of a tight budget on a brownfield site. Shortlisted RIBA Awards 2006. One of nation's favourite TV houses.
properties.name: 15 and a half Consort Road

properties.description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. NOTE: Closed on Monday 19 September
properties.name: UPDATED: City Information Centre

properties.description: Small 1970s concrete building with a raised lantern. Designed to fit in with older buildings in the conservation area , and make the most of the split-level site. Architect Trevor Dannatt. Grade ll Listed.
properties.name: Blackheath Quaker Meeting House

properties.description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.
properties.name: Pushkin House

properties.description: New building as an urban accent - two independent houses atop each other. Contemporary in design it draws from the tectonic composition of adjacent Victorian houses. Features include rain water harvesting,  roof garden, solar water heating.
properties.name: 264 Westbourne Park Road

properties.description: LMA's older building was built in the late 1930s for the Temple Press and has many original features.   Purpose built extension in early 1990s for archival storage. Public rooms remodelled by Bisset Adams in 2000s.
properties.name: London Metropolitan Archives

properties.description: The home of the Royal Astronomical Society since 1874, refurbished in 2007. Part of the extension to Burlington House to provide accommodation for learned societies.
properties.name: Burlington House: Royal Astronomical Society

properties.description: Built thanks to a generous gift from local benefactress, Mrs Lavinia Keene, St Patrick's was consecrated in July 1940 and is unusual in style. The concrete and brick interior contrasts with the dramatic, colourful reredos. Grade II listed.
properties.name: St Patrick's Church

properties.description: A public hall, theatre and gallery in grand Edwardian style. Grade II listed, Stanley made fun of the Victorian style with grand ornamentation. It reflects Stanley's interest in science, the arts and public cultural improvement.
properties.name: Stanley Arts

properties.description: A vital community garden offering a model for maximum good for communities and for the environment on a small urban plot. It is now a site of Local Importance for Nature Conservation. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.
properties.name: Dalston Eastern Curve Garden

properties.description: 4-storey multi-purpose, state of the art library and archives building.
properties.name: Dalston C.L.R. James Library & Hackney Archives

properties.description: St John's Gate in Clerkenwell dates from 1504 and was built for the Knights Hospitaller. 19th and early 20th century additions by Richard Norman Shaw and John Oldrid Scott. Grade I listed. Home to the Museum of the Order of St John.
properties.name: Museum of the Order of St John

properties.description:
A modern, low energy and highly flexible studio for architects, landscape architects and urban designers within a former industrial
building.
properties.name: Levitt Bernstein's Studio

properties.description: One of only 2 schools designed using Ernő Goldfinger's school building system - precast reinforced concrete frame with brick infill. Mural of school subjects by Gordon Cullen. Grade II* listed. Bouncing Off the Wall C20th Arts Fair 12-5
properties.name: Greenside Primary School

properties.description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.
properties.name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst

properties.description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Everything Flows', a major exhibition exploring the work of Zaha Hadid Design.
properties.name: Roca London Gallery

properties.description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
properties.name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower

properties.description: A former Victorian workhouse that has been transformed through LB Camden's Community Investment Programme into a state of the art facility for 50 homeless people laid out around a beautiful suntrap courtyard.
properties.name: Mount Pleasant

properties.description: The concrete framed structure of this apartment building adjusts to its irregularly shaped corner plot. Exposed beams and columns support lime-washed interiors and a scratched stucco façade forms an abstract expression to the street.
properties.name: Black Stone House

properties.description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.
properties.name: Kaymet Factory

properties.description: Two railway arches have been repurposed into a ceramic studio.
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Hoxton - E2

properties.description: Ceramics centre for the Lee Valley, covering the entire top floor of an old hardware factory. Three rooms, providing just over 8000 sq ft of floor space; the main room is capped by its original saw-tooth glass roof feature.
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Leyton - E10

properties.description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
properties.name: Cannizaro Studios

properties.description: Grade II listed building dating back to 1270. Following the dissolution of Christ Church Priory in Orpington in the 1530s, the house became a rectory. Additions were built in 1959 to put in a library.
properties.name: The Priory, Orpington

properties.description: Built in the Georgian style, the Guildhall brought together Kingston's administrative functions. Purpose-built Magistrates Courts were included in the building, part of which are now home to Kingston History Centre.
properties.name: Kingston Guildhall and History Centre

properties.description: London’s biggest open-access workshop, Bloqs, partners with the platform for architect-makers, Gubns, to host a series of tours, a metal workshop, and a party to celebrate all makers: https://www.eventbrite.com/cc/gubns-bloqs-1113879
properties.name: Gubns @ Bloqs: Tour, Workshop, Party

properties.description: This former factory was refurbished in 2011 by SPACE to provide studios for artists and creative makers. Weber Industries, a bespoke fabrication and custom design studio, has operated in the street-facing ground floor studios since 2012.
properties.name: Studio 11G Weber Industries

properties.description: The Small Beer Brewery was founded in 2017 by James Grundy and  Felix James. It is the first of its kind, specialising in brewing world class beer at a sociable strength.
properties.name: Small Beer Brewery

properties.description: A church building has occupied this sight for at least a thousand years.  Destroyed in the Great Fire of 1666, but rebuilt in the 1670s. Known as a Wren church, the architect was Nicholas Young.
properties.name: The City Churches: St. Michael Cornhill

properties.description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.
properties.name: St Michael and All Angels Church

properties.description: A House for Artists is an ambitious project, designed to provide affordable, sustainable housing for artists, who will offer long-term civic and cultural engagement for communities in Barking Town Centre. Drop in to the creative workshop.
properties.name: A House for Artists

properties.description: A neighborhood theatre, music and arts venue using cultural events to bring people together. We pride ourselves on being a welcoming space celebrating everyone's creativity from children to emerging producers to experienced artists.
properties.name: Streatham Space Project - Photography Exhibition: The Fighting Spirit of South London

properties.description: This transformation of a derelict pub into an architecture studio doubles up as a gallery and lecture theatre. The new office is an example of the practice’s approach towards existing structures and intelligent architectural interventions.
properties.name: Jonathan Tuckey Design Studio

properties.description: Crystal Palace Bowl is a South London icon: A venue of legends from Pink Floyd to Bob Marley, with a Stirling Prize nominated sculptural stage, revived from ruin by a local community campaign and ready to host the next generation of talent!
properties.name: Crystal Palace Bowl

properties.description:
The Church was built in 1839/41 as a white 'Hall-Church'. 
The 1870s Gothic Revivalism was overseen to a very high standard, by James Brooks and helped by 10 top craftsmen of the day. We also have a WWI Memorial by Violet Pinwill.
properties.name: St Margaret's Church, Lee

properties.description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
properties.name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale

properties.description: The former sports pavilion and its large outdoor are used as a community hub by Company Drinks. The multifunctional building and garden have recently been upgraded alongside a stakeholder-led physical and cultural access concept and design.
properties.name: Company Drinks/Barking Park Outdoor Bowls Pavilion

properties.description:
London is known for its rooftops. The Roof Garden at The Post Building has been designed as a one-off location for enjoyment, work and wellness looking out over some of its most memorable.

Open to the public 7 days a week!
properties.name: The Post Building

properties.description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."
properties.name: Museum of Neoliberalism

properties.description: A low energy refurbishment of an Edwardian house, with rear extension and loft conversion. Wood fibre insulation, MVHR, airtightness layer, triple glazing, timber structure and low embodied energy materials.
properties.name: 1 Halliwick Road

properties.description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men’s club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.
properties.name: The Mildmay Club

properties.description: A radical transformation of an Edwardian Semi that has been completely opened up and renovated with bold materials and bright colours. A stage-set mountain is elevated on an exposed structure to form the striking rear extension.
properties.name: Mountain View House

properties.description: Taylor Court and Chatto Court, together with Wilmott Court, form a pair of award-winning mixed-tenure housing, accommodating 45 new homes and commissioned by the Hackney Council on two sites at the edge of the post-war Frampton Park Estate.
properties.name: Taylor & Chatto Courts and Wilmott Court, Frampton Park Estate

properties.description: 1 Finsbury Avenue is a Grade II listed building constructed in the early 1980s by Arup Associates (Peter Foggo). As the first building in the Broadgate development it was significant in defining the speculative office typology in London.
properties.name: 1 Finsbury Avenue

properties.description: Centred on Spring Grove House, once Sir Joseph Banks home the 1850s vision was for John Taylor Jnr designed grand villas.  Today's  wider architecture includes a former college by John Norton & P Massey plus quirky arts & crafts properties.
properties.name: Exploring Spring Grove Isleworth

properties.description: The Garden of Earthly Delights is a community garden and a "meanwhile" space to raise awareness of empty spaces in the city, grow food for the local community and increase biodiversity. We hold workshops and events to which all are welcome.
properties.name: GARDEN OF EARTHLY DELIGHTS🌱🐝🍅🦋

properties.description: A first of its kind global arts destination, Cromwell Place is located in five Grade II Listed townhouses in South Kensington. Home to some of the world’s most exciting rotating art exhibitors with a range in specialties.
properties.name: Cromwell Place

properties.description: UCL PEARL is a brand new building designed to be a laboratory that can "house the world" so that we can create different environments from around the world for experiments about people and the environment around them.
properties.name: UCL PEARL

properties.description: The London Screen Academy is a unique learning environment in a heritage building transformed from a disused radio and television factory into a world class specialist sixth form education facility.
properties.name: London Screen Academy

properties.description: Early 20th C Grade II* listed church designed by CH Reilly. Byzantine in structure but prefiguring Modernism in its aesthetic, Nairn judged it “the best church of its date in London”, Reilly “the building I should like to be remembered by”.
properties.name: St Barnabas' Church and Mission Hall

properties.description:
Original Anderson Shelter, set in concrete and covered in earth.
The shelter is in the back garden of a four storey 1850s terraced house. Access to the house is down five steps.  Access to the shelter is down four deep steps.
properties.name: Anderson WW2 Bomb Shelter

properties.description: Ethelburga Tower is a 17-storey block of flats near Battersea Park.  The building was designed by the LCC  Architects Dept with Ove Arup & Partners as consulting engineers.  It was built by Tersons of Finchley and completed in 1966.
properties.name: Ethelburga Tower, Battersea

properties.description:
Semi-detached residential 2-bed house totally refurbished by the owner-architect.
The main works included demolition of str. walls to achieve open plan living, new bathrooms, kitchen, porch, windows, green roof, UFH and insulation.
properties.name: 186A Uxbridge Road

properties.description:
An industrial heritage site that was the hub of one of London’s first major pieces of urban infrastructure.
Its 18th and 19th century buildings will be restored by Tim Ronalds Architects to create the Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration.
properties.name: Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration - New River Head

properties.description: Completely carbon neutral terraced house following a retrofit solar, batteries and air source heat pump installation. Existing radiators, double glazing and roof / loft insulation.
properties.name: 23 Sedgeford Road

properties.description:
IPC, Ealing opened their winning extended building in 2018, designed by Piercy architects. 
The original 1912 chapel designed by John Ninian Comper and  is a grade 2 listed building is still intact and was integrated into the new design
properties.name: International Presbyterian Church

properties.description: C3 is home to Bureau, a members club at the heart of Design District. Its undulating white facade creates informal pockets of space on the interior, ideal for flexible working models.
properties.name: C3 - Bureau

properties.description: Designed by Charles Barry Jr in the Victorian Gothic style, it has been a landmark in Dulwich since it was painted by the French Impressionist Camille Pissarro in 1870. There is a fine fresco painted by Sir Edward Poynter in the chancel.
properties.name: St Stephen's Church, Dulwich

properties.description: The Family Kitchen & Shop, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, designed by architects HOK with front of house interiors by Mizzi Studio and Lumsden Design, is an environmentally driven, education-led food space for visitors of all ages.
properties.name: The Family Kitchen, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew

properties.description: A pre- 2nd WW - 1933 - now beautifully refurbished brick built sports pavilion surrounded by the fields of Tooting Common.
properties.name: Woodfield Pavilion

properties.description: For NOW Gallery’s 2022 Art Commission JeeYoung Lee has created an environment inspired by memories, dreams, emotions, and her personal experience. The artist reinterprets her psychological landscape and thoughts into this environment.
properties.name: 'Maiden Voyage' by JeeYoung Lee

properties.description: A low-energy, prefabricated Canadian Douglas fir rear extension to the garden flat of a converted Edwardian terraced house.
properties.name: Douglas Fir House

properties.description: A tour of one of the largest and best preserved early Victorian squares and gardens in London, also with a magnificent and original public library of 1906, which shows Byzantine and Art Nouveau influences, and a remarkable Gothic church.
properties.name: Thornhill Square

properties.description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden
properties.name: Walworth Garden

properties.description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event
properties.name: People's Museum Somers Town

properties.description: Blenheim Gardens Estate was designed and built in the late 1960s - early 1970s by Lambeth’s Architecture Department under Ted Hollamby. It marks the shift from system-built high-rise towards communal and pedestrian-dominated spaces.
properties.name: Blenheim Gardens Estate

properties.description: We will show how the long-distance trade with Canada  helped feed London’s growing population of 7 million people by 1910.  Our "museum without walls" will use virtual reality technology to to visualise historical connections.
properties.name: Millennium Mills: Feeding Edwardian London

properties.description:
A free, informal workshop session led by members of Bell Phillips Architects for children to build their own model lantern, inspired by The Tree House, and learn about architecture. 

Drop in any time between 3-5pm.
properties.name: Build your own model tree house at Elephant Park

properties.description: The project is a house and studio using innovative technologies based around principles of sustainable design. Materials were chosen to limit environmental impact and produce innovative spatial and formal solutions to urban live/work.
properties.name: 9-10 Stock Orchard Street

properties.description: Refurbishment of a first floor flat in a detached Victorian house in Hampstead, set within a conservation area, undertaken to create a bespoke contemporary minimalist family home for furniture designers.
properties.name: 17 Chesterford Gardens

properties.description:
St Matthews is Grade II listed, built 1883-4 and designed by the architect Alfred Jowers. 
It features a WW1 memorial screen designed by Reginald Hallward and stained glass some believed to be by Edward Frampton
properties.name: St Matthew's Church

properties.description: Courtyard House is a minimalist Victorian conversion featuring a serene Japanese-inspired courtyard. The house has been meticulously redesigned to offer a unique spatial experience, with a generous bright layout and handcrafted materiality.
properties.name: Courtyard House

properties.description: Two-Up Two-Down House is a reworking of a Victorian mid terrace by architects Khan Bonshek. They use imaginative spatial devices to maximise the limited floor area. Double height volumes & blurring of rooms combine to create space & light.
properties.name: Two-up Two-down House

properties.description: A small glass extension unlocks a compact Victorian terrace around a sunken kitchen, connecting upper and lower ground levels with a dramatic double height space.
properties.name: Poets Corner

properties.description: The Boleyn is a prominent landmark at a crossroads right by the former West Ham football ground. It is an exuberant piece of French-style Renaissance architecture built in 1899-1900 and reopened in June 2021 after a spectacular restoration.
properties.name: The Boleyn Tavern

properties.description: Open Studios, provides a unique glimpse to the architectural spaces and working studios of APT artists.  Over the weekend, there is also the opportunity to see our Group Show in the Gallery, curated by and featuring APT artist's work.
properties.name: Art in Perpetuity Trust

properties.description: A pavilion inspired by the organic shapes of nature and the transformational potential of seeds, currently hosting the exhibition "Saving Seed". The walls can rotate position allowing the space to perform like a seed cracking open.
properties.name: OmVed Gardens Chelsea Flower Show Pavilion

properties.description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects’ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.
properties.name: The Foundry

properties.description: The project’s aim was to extend the ground floor to provide more space for the dining area and refurbish the rest of the floor to create a coherent whole from the entrance to the garden.
properties.name: SUNDAY OPENING CANCELLED  Oswyth Road

properties.description: Peckham Courtyard is a refurbishment and extension of a Victorian, end of terrace house in Peckham, London. The clients wanted to create a better connection to the sky and garden.
properties.name: SUNDAY OPENING CANCELLED Peckham Courtyard

properties.description:
The Serpentine Coffee House overlooking the Serpentine Lake designed by Mizzi Studio, with its undulating brass canopy roof that echoes a stingray’s flight through water,  has added a
new architectural landmark to London’s Hyde Park.
properties.name: The Serpentine Coffee House, The Royal Parks, Opposite The Serpentine Gallery

properties.description: The Migration Museum is located inside the Lewisham Shopping Centre.
properties.name: Migration Museum

properties.description: Old Kent Road Arts Club is a community project space that lives inside an old sofa shop on Old Kent Road. Come and see how we've transformed this vacant retail space into a thriving creative hub that offers free activities for all ages.
properties.name: Old Kent Road Arts Club

properties.description: The new ceramics studio occupies the top floor of a beautiful old saw-toothed factory building within the Crawley Road industrial estate, one of several new creative businesses joining the area
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Haringey - N22

properties.description: Former indoor garden design workshop converted into a open-access ceramics studio.
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Highgate - N6

properties.description: Visit New London Architecture's pop-up gallery at Westfield Stratford City to see the largest model of London. Celebrate the 10-year anniversary of the Games and learn more about the past and future of Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park.
properties.name: New London Architecture

properties.description: The Experimental Weave Lab is the City of London’s first contemporary weaving studio. For Open House London we are throwing open the doors to our studio for a work in progress exhibition and live weaving.
properties.name: The Experimental Weave Lab

properties.description:
Home & Studio for Family, Architecture & Movement, part of the
hidden creative side of Clarence Mews. Includes An exhibition of the 'Purbeckian Masque' from Arts University Bournemouth M.Arch students
properties.name: 40 Clarence Mews

properties.description: The long terrace at 17a–79b Mansfield Road was the last part of the post-war Gospel Oak Redevelopment Area to be completed, and formed part of the London Borough of Camden’s ‘Golden Era’ of housing under borough architect Sydney Cook.
properties.name: 17a–79b Mansfield Road (access to two flats)

properties.description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
properties.name: St Mary's Church Bromley

properties.description: Celebrate the best writing about architects and the city at AHMM’s pop-up bookshop at Morag Myerscough’s Atoll. We’ve curated a special collection of books and maps by established publishers, smaller independents and Open City itself.
properties.name: Open Bookshop at 1 Finsbury Avenue

properties.description: We are opening the doors of our 3D Printing Studio at the Design District for all to experience the wonders of 3D printing. Come learn about this innovative technology, touch the materials, and see 3D printers in action!
properties.name: 3D Printing at Design District

properties.description: Wizard Works, London's cutest adventure bike bag brand, will be opening their studio in North Greenwich's Design District for a behind the scenes look at all things bag making.
properties.name: Wizard Works Open Studio

properties.description: A Grade II listed motor garage and petrol station built in the style of a Japanese pagoda in 1928. Now a Tesco Express.
properties.name: "Chinese" Garage

properties.description: Altab Ali Park was renamed in 1998 after a murdered 25-year-old Bangladeshi Sylheti clothing worker. Formerly known as St. Mary's Park, it is the site of the old 14 C white church, St. Mary Matfelon which gave Whitechapel its name.
properties.name: Altab Ali Park

properties.description: Kin Structures and residents of Orchard Gardens estate have been making art to explore new futures for the local community centre. Join this final event to participate in their journey of reimagining community centres for the 21st century.
properties.name: Reimagining Orchard Gardens Community Centre

properties.description: Wates Built 1960s Semi, extended & renovated into a vibrant, colourful stylish 21st Century home. Embracing Midcentury & Modern design with Bold Colours, Patterns & Materials to create the feeling of space, light & individuality throughout.
properties.name: LivingFunky House

properties.description:
Learn about architect Julian Sofaer and join in with activities related to our community garden.

Draw local endangered flowers: 
Sunday 3pm - 4pm

Learn about fruit & veg grown locally: 
Saturday 2.30pm - 4pm 
Sunday 1pm - 2.30pm
properties.name: Canal club community centre reopening party

properties.description: Uncommon Projects moved into their new showroom in June 2022. The showroom will be open for walk in visitors for the duration of Open House.
properties.name: Uncommon Projects

properties.description: Visit our studio in David Kohn Architects' building A4 in Design District and see where we formulate and manufacture all of our products. Sample our full range and take part in a perfume oil making workshop.
properties.name: Homework Open Studio (A4)

properties.description: A pair of un-identical twin buildings that slope steeply on one side to open views through Design District London. The buildings provide light industrial spaces on three levels with workshops and retail at ground floor.
properties.name: B2

properties.description:
A reconfiguration and additional floor to a purpose built maisonette in South West London. 

The interior space and circulation are opened up with Oak detailing throughout. Externally a Copper roof drapes over the new structure.
properties.name: Copper Maisonette
